text:
Public transport companies etc
	Removal of certain disabilities and requirements for consent
		Part 4 of the TA 1985 (which makes provision for the establishment ofpublic transport companies and for the powers of Passenger TransportAuthorities etc in relation to them) is amended as follows.
		In section 74 (disabilities of directors of public transport companies),omit subsections (3) to (12).
		Each of the following (which require the consent of the Secretary of Statefor the exercise of certain powers) is omitted—
			section 75(3) (subscription for, or acquisition or disposal of, certainshares, securities or other property or assets etc);
			section 79(3) (making or guaranteeing of certain loans);
			section 79(7) (guarantees etc in connection with disposals of certainshares, securities or other property or assets etc);
			in section 79(8) (provision of financial assistance by way of grants,loans, etc) the words “, with the consent of the Secretary of State,”.

Appeals to the Transport Tribunal
	Appeals to the Transport Tribunal
		In Schedule 4 to the TA 1985 (constitution, powers and proceedings of theTransport Tribunal) paragraph 9 (powers of tribunal on appeal fromdetermination of traffic commissioner) is amended as follows.
		In sub-paragraph (1), for the words from “under” to “1999” substitute“under any of the enactments specified in sub-paragraph (1A) below”.
		After sub-paragraph (1) insert—
			“(1A)The enactments are—
			  * the 1981 Act;
			  * this Act;
			  * the Goods Vehicles (Licensing of Operators) Act 1995;
			  * the Road Transport (Passenger Vehicles Cabotage) Regulations 1999;
			  * section 155 of the Transport Act 2000;
			  * section 75 of the Local Transport Act 2008.”.

London charging schemes: 10 year plan for share
	In Schedule 23 to the GLA Act 1999 (road user charging) paragraphs 19 to 24are amended as follows.
	In paragraph 19 (charging authority’s 10 year plan for their share ofproceeds of scheme) omit sub-paragraphs (3)(a) and (4).
	In paragraph 20 (charging authority’s 4 year programme for their share)—
		omit sub-paragraphs (2)(a), (3) and (4);
		in sub-paragraph (5) after “prepared and” insert “(where so required)”.
	In paragraph 21 (Authority’s 10 year plan for the redistributed portion)—
		in sub-paragraph (2) omit “and submit to the Secretary of State”;
		omit sub-paragraph (4).
	In paragraph 22 (Authority’s 4 year programmes for the redistributedportion)—
		omit sub-paragraph (3);
		in sub-paragraph (4) omit “and approved” in both places where those wordsoccur.
	In paragraph 23 (non-compliance with paragraph 20 or 22)—
		in sub-paragraph (1) after “prepared and” insert “(where so required)”;
		in sub-paragraph (2) omit “and approved”.
	In paragraph 24 (4 year programmes: amendment, replacement and voluntarystatements)—
		in sub-paragraph (1) after “prepared and” insert “(where so required)”;
		in paragraph (c) of sub-paragraph (3), omit the words from “and, ifapproved” to the end;
		in sub-paragraph (5)(a) after “prepared and” insert “(where so required”;
		omit sub-paragraphs (6)(a) and (7);
		in sub-paragraph (8) after “prepared and” in both places where those wordsoccur insert “(where so required)”;
		in sub-paragraph (10)—
		after “prepared and” in the first place where those words occur insert“(where so required)”;
		omit “prepared and approved” in the second place where those words occur;
		at the beginning of paragraph (a) insert “prepared and approved”;
		at the beginning of paragraph (b) insert “prepared”.

Foreign-registered vehicles
	Disclosure of information relating to foreign-registered vehicles
		After section 49 of the Road Safety Act [2006 (c.49)](/id/ukpga/2006/49?view=plain "Go to item of legislation") (disclosure toforeign authorities of licensing and registration information) insert—
		“49ADisclosure of information relating to foreign-registered vehicles
			The Secretary of State may disclose information to which subsection (2)applies to any person or body referred to in subsection (3) (subject to anyrestrictions mentioned in relation to the person or body).
			This subsection applies to information that—
				is derived from particulars contained in a register of vehicles that ismaintained in a country or territory outside the United Kingdom, and
				has been obtained by the Secretary of State from the authority orauthorities of that country or territory with responsibility under the law ofthat country or territory for maintaining the register.
			The persons and bodies are—
				a local authority, where the disclosure is made for any purpose connectedwith the investigation of—
				an offence, or
				a road traffic contravention;
				Transport for London, where the disclosure is made for such a purpose;
				the Department of the Environment in Northern Ireland, where the disclosureis made for any purpose connected with the investigation of an offence;
				the Department for Regional Development in Northern Ireland, where thedisclosure is made for any purpose connected with the investigation of a roadtraffic contravention;
				the chief officer of police of a police force in England and Wales;
				the chief constable of a police force maintained under the Police(Scotland) Act 1967;
				a member of the Police Service of Northern Ireland;
				an officer of Revenue and Customs;
				an inspector of taxes, where the disclosure is made for any purposeconnected with any tax liability to which a person is or may be subject, orthe amount of any such liability;
				a person who the Secretary of State is satisfied has reasonable cause forseeking disclosure of the information.
			The Secretary of State may charge a reasonable fee in respect of the costof—
				obtaining, or seeking to obtain, information falling within subsection(2)(a);
				supplying information under subsection (1).
			Nothing in this section affects any other power of the Secretary of Stateto disclose information.
			In this section—
				  * “local authority” means—
				a county council in England;
				a metropolitan district council;
				a non-metropolitan district council for an area for which there is no countycouncil;
				a London borough council;
				the Common Council of the City of London;
				the Council of the Isles of Scilly;
				a county council or county borough council in Wales;
				a council constituted under section 2 of the Local Government etc. (Scotland)Act 1994;
					  * “road traffic contravention” means—
				in relation to England and Wales, any contravention falling within Schedule 7to the Traffic Management Act 2004;
				in relation to Scotland, any act or omission that would have been an offencebut for paragraph 1(4) or (as the case may be) 2(4) of Schedule 3 to the RoadTraffic Act 1991 (control of parking in permitted and special parking areas);
				in relation to Northern Ireland, any contravention falling within Schedule 1to the Traffic Management (Northern Ireland) Order 2005 ([2005 No. 1964 (N.I.14)](/id/nisi/2005/1964?view=plain "Go to item of legislation"));
					  * “tax” has the meaning given by section 118(1) of the Taxes Management Act 1970.”.
	Use of information relating to foreign-registered vehicles
		After section 49A of the Road Safety Act [2006 (c.49)](/id/ukpga/2006/49?view=plain "Go to item of legislation") insert—
		“49BUse of information relating to foreign-registered vehicles
			The Secretary of State may use information to which section 49A(2) appliesfor any of the purposes referred to in subsection (2).
			The purposes are—
				to check the accuracy of information which has been obtained underregulations made by virtue of section 22A(2) of the Vehicle Excise andRegistration Act 1994 (vehicle identity checks);
				to check the accuracy of records maintained by the Secretary of State inconnection with any functions exercisable by the Secretary of State under orby virtue of that Act;
				to check the accuracy of records maintained, or caused to be maintained,under section 45(6B) or 49(3A) of the Road Traffic Act 1988 (records ofexaminations of goods and other vehicles);
				to promote compliance with section 47 or 53 of that Act (obligatory testcertificates for goods and other vehicles);
				where appropriate, to amend or supplement any information mentioned in theforegoing provisions of this subsection or information contained in anyrecords so mentioned;
				to trace a non-resident parent (within the meaning of the Child Support(Information, Evidence and Disclosure) Regulations 1992 ([S.I.1992/1812](/id/uksi/1992/1812?view=plain "Go to item of legislation"))).”.

Part 8Supplementary provisions
	Repeals 
		Schedule 7 contains repeals.
	Interpretation 
		In this Act—
		  * “the TA 1968” means the Transport Act [1968 (c. 73)](/id/ukpga/1968/73?view=plain "Go to item of legislation"); 
		  * “the PPVA 1981” means the Public Passenger Vehicles Act [1981 (c. 14)](/id/ukpga/1981/14?view=plain "Go to item of legislation"); 
		  * “the TA 1985” means the Transport Act [1985 (c. 67)](/id/ukpga/1985/67?view=plain "Go to item of legislation"); 
		  * “the GLA Act 1999” means the Greater London Authority Act [1999 (c. 29)](/id/ukpga/1999/29?view=plain "Go to item of legislation"); 
		  * “the TA 2000” means the Transport Act [2000 (c. 38)](/id/ukpga/2000/38?view=plain "Go to item of legislation"). 
	Extent 
		Subject to subsections (2) and (3), this Act extends to England and Walesonly.
		The following provisions also extend to Scotland—
			sections 1 to 6;
			section 47 and Schedule 3;
			sections 53 and 54(1) to (7);
			sections 55 and 56;
			sections 57 to 61;
			section 68(1) and (2);
			section 72;
			section 74;
			section 119;
			section 122;
			section 125;
			section 126;
			section 128;
			sections 129 and 130;
			sections 132, 134, 135 and this section;
			the repeals in Part 3 of Schedule 7 relating to sections 22 and 23 of theTA 1985, and section 131 so far as relating to those repeals.
		The following provisions also extend to Northern Ireland—
			section 122;
			sections 129 and 130;
			sections 132, 134, 135 and this section.
	Commencement 
		The following provisions of this Act come into force on the day on whichthis Act is passed—
			section 77(10);
			this Part, other than section 131 and Schedule 7;
			any power under or by virtue of this Act to make regulations or an order.
		Sections 55, 56, 122, 123, 124 and 127 come into force at the end of theperiod of 2 months beginning with the day on which this Act is passed.
		Subject to subsection (4), the other provisions of this Act come into forceon an appointed day.
		Any repeal in Schedule 7 (and section 131 so far as relating to the repeal)comes into force in the same way as the provisions of this Act to which therepeal relates.
		In this section “appointed day” means such day or days as the Secretary ofState may by order made by statutory instrument appoint.
		The power conferred by subsection (5) is exercisable as respects Wales bythe Welsh Ministers (and not the Secretary of State) in relation to—
			Part 2;
			Part 3;
			in Part 4, sections 64, 65(1), 68 to 71 and 75;
			in Part 6, the amendments of the TA 2000.
		An order under subsection (5)—
			may appoint different days for different purposes;
			may make incidental, consequential, supplemental or transitional provisionor savings.
	Short title
		This Act may be cited as the Local Transport Act 2008.
